SIMPLE: obtrude
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obtrude
<hw>Ob*trude"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Obtruded</conjf>, <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Obtruding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>obtrudere</ets>,
<ets>obtrusum</ets>; <ets>ob</ets> (see <er>Ob-</er>) +
<ets>trudere</ets> to thrust. See <er>Threat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To thrust impertinently; to present to a person without warrant or
solicitation; <as>as, to <ex>obtrude</ex> one's self upon a company; to
<ex>obtrude</ex> one's opinion on another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The objects of our senses <qex>obtrude</qex> their particular
ideas upon our minds, whether we will or no.</q>
<rj><qau>Lock.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To offer with unreasonable importunity; to urge
unduly or against the will.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obtrude</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Obtrude
<hw>Ob*trude"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To thrust one's self upon a
company or upon attention; to intrude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To <er>Obtrude</er>, <er>Intrude</er>.</syn>
<usage> To <xex>intrude</xex> is to thrust one's self into a place,
society, etc., without right, or uninvited; to <xex>obtrude</xex> is to
force one's self, remarks, opinions, etc., into society or upon persons
with whom one has no such intimacy as to justify such
boldness.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obtruder</ent>⟦br⟧
